In [15]:
#create formula to calculate inconsistency between given & calculated values
def inconsistency(df_name, df_x ,df_y, n):
    df_name=np.abs(df_x-df_y)
    df=[df_name <= n]
In [16]:
#Convert Start & End Time to date time & Check integrity of duration
df.start_time = pd.to_datetime(df.start_time)
df.end_time = pd.to_datetime(df.end_time)
df['calc_duration'] = df['end_time']-df['start_time']
df['calc_duration'] =df['calc_duration']/np.timedelta64(1,'s')
df['dur_diff']=0
inconsistency(df['dur_diff'], df['calc_duration'], df['duration_sec'], 1)

# classify start dates & times
df['start_date'] = df.start_time.dt.strftime('%Y-%m-%d')
df['start_hour'] = df.start_time.dt.strftime('%H')
df['start_day'] = df.start_time.dt.strftime('%A')
df['start_month'] =  df.start_time.dt.strftime('%B')
df['start_year'] = df.start_time.dt.strftime('%Y')
# classify end dates & times
df['end_date'] = df.end_time.dt.strftime('%Y-%m-%d')
df['end_hour'] = df.end_time.dt.strftime('%H')
df['end_day'] = df.end_time.dt.strftime('%A')
df['end_month'] =  df.end_time.dt.strftime('%B')
df['end_year'] = df.end_time.dt.strftime('%Y')
#drop start & end time stamps
df.drop(['start_time', 'end_time'], axis=1, inplace=True)

#Create & merge new data frames for calculated data on start id, longitude & latitude
start_id = pd.DataFrame(df.groupby('start_station_name')['start_station_id'].mean())
start_long = pd.DataFrame(df.groupby('start_station_name')['start_station_longitude'].mean())
start_lat = pd.DataFrame(df.groupby('start_station_name')['start_station_latitude'].mean())
df_start=pd.merge(start_id, start_long,  on='start_station_name', how = 'inner')
df_start=pd.merge(df_start, start_lat, on='start_station_name', how ='inner')
df=pd.merge(df, df_start, on = 'start_station_name', how = 'inner')

#Calculating Vecotorized Linear Distance between start & stop stations
def haversine(lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2, to_radians=True, earth_radius=6371):
    """
    slightly modified version: of http://stackoverflow.com/a/29546836/2901002

    Calculate the great circle distance between two points
    on the earth (specified in decimal degrees or in radians)

    All (lat, lon) coordinates must have numeric dtypes and be of equal length.

    """
    if to_radians:
        lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2 = np.radians([lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2])

    a = np.sin((lat2-lat1)/2.0)**2 + np.cos(lat1) * np.cos(lat2) * np.sin((lon2-lon1)/2.0)**2

    return earth_radius * 2 * np.arcsin(np.sqrt(a))*1000

Univariant Exploration Observations¶

1- Gender Split: Males = 74.6% Females = 23.3% Other = 2.1%

2- 90.6% of users are subscribers & only 9.4% are customers

3- Mean Trip Duration is slighly slightly higher than 11 minutes, around half the trips is less than 8.5 minutes & the majority of the trips are of 4.5 minutes

4- Average trip distance is around 1.7 Km. where half of them is more than 1.429 Km & Most trips have a 0 distance as they started & stopped in the same station which suggest either a quick errand or recreational use

5- Almost 10% of users soley rely on bike share which is a pretty good percentage

6- Peak days seem to be during weekdays which suggests the use of bikeshare for commuting to & from work

7- Peak hours seem to be around 8-9am & 5-6pm which agrees with the above commuting hypothesis

8- There was a sudden drop in demand on February 13th - a weekday- (the day before valentine's) & an unpredicted increase in demand for February 25th - a weekend-. the reasons behind those two dates are still unknown

9- Most users lie in the range between 18 & 57 years old with some outliers ranging up to the age of 120 years old.

10- The distribution between age groups shows that 38.6% of users are between 27-34, 23.5% between 35-44, 22.8% between 18-26, 12.7% between 45-59 & 2.4% above the age of 60

Bivariant Exploration Observations¶

1- Males use Ford Go Bike the least average distance followed by females & then other genders but the mean difference is around 150 meters

2- one time customers have around 12% more distance than subscribers

3- There doesn't seem to be a correlation between duration & distance except: a- the minimum duration for each distance increases as the distance increase b- the main cluster of points lie between 5minutes & 1 hour c- There's a significant number of trips with zero distance but a large duration which suggests the errand/recreational use

4- People that use bike share for all trips seem to travel distances 20% of the average user that does't 100% rely on bike share in addition to that exclusive bike share users seem to have higher consentration of trips that have distances around 850 m & 1350 m

5- Mean distance travelled on weekdays is around 8% higher than that of the weekends

6- Peak distance seems to be consitent with the hypothesis of using Ford Go Bike on typical work commuting times with some expectional error margins between 2 & 5am

7- the average distance travelled per day seems to be consistent with both the weekday vs. weekend statement & the Feb 13th & Feb 25th are still showing unexpected values

8- The Average distance travelled per age group seems to disagree with the count when it comes to age group split as the majority of the users seem to fall between 1050m & 1150m with a small error margin below the 50m while more senior users seem to have varying fluctuation in their distance as it is logical to drop with age but it's unexplained for users above the age of 100

9- Mean duration per gender from smallest to largest is Males, Females & Then others which is consistent with distances but with a maximum deviation of around 4 minutes which is around 35% of the average trip length which suggest that the average speed for males is the highest

10-The mean duration of one time customers is more than double than that of subscribers which suggest that subscribers are usually faster in their trips & also the standard deviation for distance in subscribers is smaller than that of customers which is inline with the commuting hypothesis

11- weekends seem to have higher average durations than weekdays which is against what we have seen in distances which suggests that are usually slower on weekends and implies that more zero distance trips (errands or recreational) happen on weekends.

12- The durations seem to drop in the commuting times in addition to having outliers & a wide margin of error in trips between midnight & dawn. which can somehow be explained by 2 far fetched hypothesis of: 1- People mainly use Ford Go bike to escape traffic in commuting times as durations decrease with the increase of the distance which somehow implies that traffic usually peaks during commuting hours. in addition to the recrational use mentioned before 2- people might forget to properly end their trips when riding at late nights which can explain the huge error & sudden spike in numbers but this needs a totally seperate investigations

13- The younger group of people almost all have equal mean trip durations with a small error margin which suggest that people below 45 years of age have a typical use for commuting while the older age groups till the age of 80 start using For Go Bike for higher duration which can be either because of the recreational use or the slower speed that comes with age and the users above 80 show a significant drop in the mean to fully suggest recreational use at an average that is below 5 minutes for 80-99 & below 7 minutes for above 100

14- It seems that there's more consistency in the peak durations for weekdays with the commuting hypothesis and on weekend it seems that it's more of a normal distribution around the afternoon

15- The mean age for weekends is lower than the mean age for weekdays

MultiVariant Exploration Observations¶

1- The percentage of females is higher in customers than that of subscribers, also the number of trips for customers doesn't seem to vary much between weekdays & weekends which suggests that the majority of errand/recreational trips are done by customers

2- The highest percentage of nonbinary users lies in the age groups between 27 to 44, also the daily usage doesn't seem to depend much on the gender

3- There is consistency across genders & age groups regarding more demand on weekdays than weekends & also the age group split with some exceptions regarding the age group distribution in non-binary users as the age groups vary significantly between one day and another & also vary vs. the typical age group split

4- It looks like that females & other genders have more subscribers than customers specially in the older age groups, also the average distance between genders doesn't seem to vary significantly but their error margin seem to increase with the decrease of the number of samples which is logical. weirdly, looks like females & non-binary users above the age of 100 seem to have a very small error margin and they both seem to be soley subscribers. The most obvious error margins are in the age group between 60-79 & highest amongst females & nonbinary users

5- Customers typically have higher fluctuation in durations vs. subscribers and we can also see similiar trends as the ones seen in distances travelled as they don't fully rely on Ford Go Bike for the routine routes

6- Hours peak during weekdays at 8 am & 17 pm as suggested before in all genders with the exception of Non-Binary as they peak at 5 & 6 pm

7- Thursday seems to have the highest demand in these hours regardless of the gender

8- Finally looks like the percentage of non-binary users on weekend is higher than that of the other genders
